### Description

Hey team,

I've been working with the ML-KEM implementation in wolfSSL and noticed something that feels like a gap - there's no dedicated key validation function like Dilithium has with `wc_dilithium_check_key()`. 

When I'm importing keys from external sources or debugging key management issues, it would be really helpful to have a quick way to verify that an `MlKemKey` structure is actually valid without having to run full cryptographic operations. Right now, if I suspect a key is malformed, my only option is to either manually inspect the structure (which is error-prone) or try to use it in an operation and see if it fails.

Looking at the code:
- Dilithium has `wc_dilithium_check_key()` for consistency checks
- ML-KEM only has encode/decode functions but no integrity validation
- The MLKEM_key_validation_feature.md in the repo actually mentions this gap

This makes ML-KEM harder to work with safely compared to the other PQC algorithms in the library.


